    <title>Razer leans into haptics with a new gaming cushion and vibrating headphones</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A picture of the Razer Freyja on a green and black background." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/UebC2ja9eOozQDU2PSuIli-A0Y4=/0x0:1500x1000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73619620/Razer_Freyja.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Razer Freyja can turn most computer chairs into haptic gaming accessories.&lt;/em&gt; | Image: Razer&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="7R1EgY"&gt;Razer has released the &lt;a href="https://razer.a9yw.net/c/482924/642901/10229?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.razer.com%2Fgaming-chairs-accessories%2Frazer-freyja&amp;amp;sharedid=theverge.com" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;Freyja gaming cushion&lt;/a&gt;, a haptic cushion that you can attach to your gaming chair, the company &lt;a href="https://press.razer.com/featured/razercon-2024/"&gt;announced&lt;/a&gt;. The cushion is $299.99, and it’s available to buy now.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="DEbH6V"&gt;The Freyja is an extension of the vibration you get from gaming controllers — except instead of just jolting your hands, it buzzes several panels positioned behind and beneath you in response to things happening in a game. &lt;/p&gt;
